export default () => {
  return 123;
}



//Rules for Reducers
//1. reducers must return any value except undefined, so reducers should 
//always have a #return 

//when you startup your application, each reducer is called exactly once. When it gets called, it's going to 
//receive two arguments: undefined and the action, and return some initial value

//set default values for your reducers to avoid that undefined in the inital state throwing an error

//2. Reducers must produce 'state' or data to be used inside of your app
//using only previous state and the action

//3. Reducers must not reach "outside of itself" to decide what value to return.
//basically, no API calls. Reducers should only be interacting with data inside of its Store.

//no api requests, no reading files on the drive, don't ask user for input, etc.

//reducers are only suppose to look at the previous state value and the action it was called with.
